<font color="#FF0000">A POINT OF VIEW</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan 24 20:56:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Excuse me, but I thought this page was dedicated to *points of view*.<br><br>
You, and I, have points of view that are no better or no worse than those of anyone else who hase posted here.<br><br>
It is my point of view that this page is a gift. In its larger sense it conveys the sense of dissent, fear, pain, remorse, abandonment, joy, reconciliation, and all the very human emotions through which the Vietnam War was experienced and is expressed.<br><br>
It is my point of view that the very act of speaking out in this forum, regardless of what was said, requires considerable courage and conviction, and should be respected. We all have a burden of pain that needs to be shared so it can be understood, a first step in a healing process.<br><br>
It is my point of view that the Vietnam War legacy is a travesty of this society. The body count continues to rise among those who were, are, and will continue to be broken, isolated, afraid, shamed, confused, and angry by the continuation of the war in their minds. <br><br>
It is important for this society to hear everyone's words. Though we cannot turn back the clock, and we are left to pull ourselves up by our own bootstraps, perhaps someone out there with a conscience will do something to prevent this from happening again. Even the acts of only one is measureable progress.<br><br>
No one &quot;knows&quot; what the Vietnam war was really about beyond their own experiences and points of view. I thank you for yours.<br><br>
May this page continue as it is. A &quot;moderator&quot; is the last thing that we need to color this beyond the color of our own words. I don't need a mouthpiece or a mommy. I need to have what I feel heard. After all, I only got here because I was &quot;moderated&quot; by an amoral bunch of brainwashers who were at their personal political extremes at a time when I didn't know any better. I do now. <br><br>
     
